post_text:
The USDA has extended its free meals program through Dec. 31, 2020. Here's what you need to know:

• There will be daily meal pickup available at RHS’ Livingston Campus from 10:00am-1:00pm, Monday-Friday. The cost of meals will be free to anyone under the age of 18. Families will be able to take meals home for the week. We are unable to provide weekend meals at this time.

• Produce and dairy boxes will be passed out on Wednesdays @ RHS' Livingston Campus from 10:00A-1:00P.

• Free meals begin TODAY Tuesday, September 8th.

• Unfortunately, we are not able to provide refunds for meals served prior to September 8, 2020.

If you have additional questions, please contact our Food Services Department at 614-501-1213.

post_text:
Over the weekend, the Reynoldsburg High School and Junior High competed in their first cross country meet held at Columbus Academy. In the Varsity Girls race, eSTEM Academy senior Avril M. placed first place with the third fastest time in the State of Ohio this season. In the Junior High boys race, STEM Middle at BRJH 8th grader Abdoul B. took first place. In the varsity boys race, eSTEM Academy senior Seth D. placed second.

Pictured is Avril M. at the meet!

post_text:
This weekend, beginning Friday, August 7 and ending Sunday, August 9, 2020 is Ohio's tax free shopping holiday. During the holiday, the following items are exempt from sales and use tax:

An item of clothing priced at $75 or less;
An item of school supplies priced at $20 or less; and
An item of school instructional material priced at $20 or less.
Additional information about Ohio’s Tax Free Holiday and FAQ’s can be found on the Ohio Department of Taxations' Website.

An item of school instructional material priced at $20 or less.

We are hosting two informational webinars where you can ask questions not answered in the RCS Virtual Academy Guide. post_text:
As our Task Force, comprised of parents, teachers, community members and RCS leadership, works to determine what a return to school will look like for the 2020-21 academic year, we wanted to gather some feedback from the community about the four options we are currently considering. Please review the four options below and choose the option that you feel best suits your child(ren)'s needs. We understand that this is not a "one size fits all" scenario, and there are still other things to consider (electives, band, choir, athletics, etc.). This is not a final decision or a vote for scenarios, as the Task Force still has another meeting to conduct, but this will help us make decisions to present to our Board of Education at the July Regular Meeting. Please also know that there are other factors that might allow for all students to return to school as normal or that may make us operate completely remote where all students stay home.

You can take the survey here: https://bit.ly/3e4mmup

Thank you for taking the time to provide your input.

post_text: Today, we celebrate Juneteenth, where, on June 19, 1865, Union General Gordon Granger arrived in Galveston, Texas. He informed the enslaved African Americans of their freedom and that the Civil War had ended. This momentous occasion has been celebrated as Juneteeth -- a combination of June and 19 -- for over 150 years. Learn about the history, celebrations and more at the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture https://nmaahc.si.edu/events/juneteenth

post_text: We just received word from the Ohio High School Athletic Association (OHSAA) that Spring sports for grades 7-12 have been cancelled for the 2020 season due to COVID19. We know this is disappointing to our student athletes, families and coaches. The Athletic Department and Treasurer are working to issue refunds for those who paid pay to participate fees. More information from the Athletic Department will be coming soon. In the meantime, if you have any questions, please contact Jacob Perkins, RCS Athletic Director or your coach.
text: We just received word from the Ohio High School Athletic Association (OHSAA) that Spring sports for grades 7-12 have been cancelled for the 2020 season due to COVID19. We know this is disappointing to our student athletes, families and coaches. The Athletic Department and Treasurer are working to issue refunds for those who paid pay to participate fees. More information from the Athletic Department will be coming soon. In the meantime, if you have any questions, please contact Jacob Perkins, RCS Athletic Director or your coach.

post_text: Utilizing our fab labs, RCS partnered with Dynalab and are making PPE for first responders in Delaware, OH. RCS is cutting the plastic and Dynalab is providing materials, leading assembly and production. We hope to make 1,500 shields.

We are proud to join other districts across the state to pay tribute to seniors everywhere who have had to sacrifice the experience of a senior year due to this historic pandemic. post_text: April 1, is Census Day. However busy you are, please make sure you complete your Census online at https://my2020census.gov/. Given our stay-at-home order from Ohio Governor Mike DeWine, this will be the best way to do it this year. The census count is particularly important for the schools. It determines the amount of federal funding distributed to states for programs that impact schools, students and families. So make sure you play your part to help us fund our schools over the next ten years!

post_text: We have been getting a lot of questions about Graduation (currently scheduled for May 26, 2020) and Prom (currently scheduled for April 25, 2020), and at one point there was a rumor that both were cancelled. Currently we are still having both events on the original dates, but we are closely monitoring the Governor's communication to make sure we are following his guidance. We have reached out to both venues and have secured some back-up dates for both events in case our plans need to change. We are also working on something we can do to ease the fears of our Seniors who are understandably sad of the timing of a national crisis. As we have more information, we will share it. Thank you for your understanding and patience.

post_text: Congratulations to Jared, one of three RCS Bus Drivers, along with Royce and John, who placed in the top 10 in the School Bus Driver Safety Road-e-o! School bus drivers throughout Ohio participate in regional road-e-o competitions in October, designed to test and increase their operational and safety skills. Top participants at each regional road-e-o move on to compete at the state-level competition. Jared placed second and will move on to States! Jared has been with the District since 2014.

post_text:
UPDATE: Paramedics have cleared the driver and students. Our Director of Transportation will remain on site until students are either picked up by their parents or at EFTCC.

This morning the bus subbing for BUS 3 was involved in a minor accident en route to the Eastland Fairfield Career Center when another vehicle hit the side mirror of the bus. No students on board were injured, but out of an abundance of caution paramedics are on the scene to check the students and driver. We have dispatched another bus to the scene to load the students onto and get them to Fairfield as quickly as possible. The school has been notified of the delay in getting to school as well. If you have any questions, please do not hesitate to contact our transportation department at 614-501-1041. We will send an update when the students have arrived at EFTCC.
